The two entities refer to different concepts: 'Romans' denotes the citizen body/people of Rome (social-political community), while 'Roman army' denotes the military organization/instrument of Roman power. They are related but not identical.

These are distinct groups: 'Romans' refers to the citizen body/polity of Rome itself, while 'Rome's allies' refers to external allied or satellite peoples who supported Rome militarily. They are related but not the same entity (one is the Roman citizen community; the other are subject/ally peoples).

The two entities refer to distinct concepts: 'Romans' denotes the citizen body/people of Rome (a social/political group), while 'Roman army' denotes the military organization/institution. They are related but not identical.

The two mentions refer to different social categories. "Italian peasant" denotes a socioeconomic type (rural peasants in Italy, described as a typical figure of the early republic gradually impoverished). "proletarii" is a specific Roman legal/class term for citizens whose contribution to the army was only to produce children (a defined class in Roman census/constitution). They are related (both lower-class rural populace), but not strictly identical: proletarii is a particular Roman class with legal connotations, whereas Italian peasant is a broader social/occupational description. Therefore they should not be merged.

The first entity ('Romans') denotes the citizen body/people of Rome (a social and political community), while the second ('Roman Senate') denotes a specific political institution/organization within Roman governance. They are related (the Senate represented the ruling class of Romans and conducted political business) but are distinct types: a people vs. an institutional body. This is not the same historical entity and should not be merged.

The two entities are different types and referents: 'Italian peasant' is a social/class collective (people) describing typical rural inhabitants, while 'Roman Republic' is a political state. They are related (peasants lived within the Roman Republic) but are not the same historical entity and should not be merged.

The two entities refer to different social groups: 'Romans' denotes the citizen body of Rome (political community with sovereignty, values, and changing socioeconomic composition), while 'slaves' denotes people without property or families below other classes. They are related (slaves existed within Roman society) but are not the same entity.

The two entities are related but not identical. "Rome's allies" refers broadly to various allied or satellite peoples who supported Rome militarily across time; it is a category that could include many different groups. "Latins" are a specific ethnic/linguistic people of central Italy (including early inhabitants of Rome and surrounding cities). While the Latins could be one of Rome’s allies at times, they are a distinct, identifiable people rather than the generic collective label "Rome's allies." Therefore they should not be merged.

One entity is a collective group of people ('Romans' — the citizen body of Rome), while the other is a specific recurring administrative event ('Roman census') used to register and classify those citizens. They are related (the census concerns Romans) but are distinct entity types (people vs event) and not identical.

'Italian peasant' refers to a class of rural free or smallholding agricultural workers in Italy (a social/economic class). 'slaves' refers to people without property or families below other classes — an enslaved status. These are distinct social categories (peasants vs slaves) and not identical entities, though both are collective people groups. They should not be merged.

The first entity is the citizen body of Rome (the Romans) — a people/collective. The second is a specific magistracy/office within Roman institutions (Tribunes of the People), an organization/officer group elected by the people. They are related (tribunes represent/protect the Roman people) but are not the same entity.

The two entities refer to distinct groups: 'Romans' denotes the citizen body of Rome (Roman citizens, a political community), while 'Rome's allies' denotes allied or satellite peoples subject to levies who were not the Roman citizen body. They are related (allies provided manpower) but are not the same entity.

The two entities refer to different kinds of collectives: one is the Roman state/empire, the other is the allied or satellite peoples who supplied manpower to Rome. They are related but not identical—the allies are distinct groups subordinate to or allied with Rome, not the Roman Empire itself.

These refer to related but distinct concepts: one is the body of Roman citizens (the people) during the Republic, the other is the Roman Republic as the political/state system. They are not strictly identical — the citizens (Romans) are a social/political collective distinct from the state (Roman Republic).

The two entities refer to different collective groups. 'Italian peasant' describes a generic rural peasant figure in the early republic, impoverished over time — a socio-economic class/occupation. 'Romans' (Roman citizens/People) denotes the citizen body/political community of Rome, which included rural agricultural citizens but is a broader political-cultural category. They are related (many Roman citizens were rural/peasant) but not identical.

Entity 1 refers to the citizen body (the people of Rome) as a socio-political group; Entity 2 refers to the Roman Republic as the state/political system. They are related but distinct: one is the population/people, the other is the state/institution. Not strictly identical, so should not be merged.

'Legions' are component units of the 'Roman army', not identical to the entire Roman armed forces. The Roman army is the overarching organization that is organized into legions (and other units). These are related but distinct entities (one is a subunit type, the other is the whole military institution).

'Legions' are component military units within the broader 'Roman army'. They are not identical: one is a specific type of unit/formation, the other is the entire armed forces that includes legions plus other elements and institutions. The descriptions and attributes show a part-whole relationship rather than co-reference, so they should not be merged.

The first entity ('legions') denotes Roman military units (the Roman legions). The second entity ('Rome's allies') denotes allied/satellite peoples who supplied manpower to Rome. These are distinct: one is an organization/unit within the Roman military, the other is external groups of people allied to Rome. They are related (legions sometimes included allied levies historically) but not identical.

The two entities refer to distinct groups: 'legions' are specific Roman military units/organizations, while 'Rome's allies' are separate allied peoples who provided manpower. They are related (allies supplied troops to the legions) but are not the same entity.

The two entities refer to different things: 'legions' are military units/organizations within the Roman army, whereas 'Roman Republic' is the state/political entity that governed Rome. They are related (legions associated with the Roman Republic) but not identical.

'legions' refers to military units of the Roman army (an organization/unit type). 'Romans' refers to the citizen body/people of Rome (a population/political community). These are related but distinct: legions are military units composed largely of Romans (and later non-Romans) and serve the Roman state, but they are not the same entity as the Roman people. Therefore they should not be merged.

The first entity refers to the Roman legions — military units of the Roman army. The second refers to the Roman ruling elite — the political/social elite who governed Rome. These are distinct types (military units vs. a governing social class) and not identical; they are related but not the same entity and should not be merged.

The two entities refer to different concepts: 'legions' are Roman military units (organizations), while 'Rome's allies' are external allied peoples/groups who provided manpower. They are related (allies supplied troops to legions) but are not identical.

'legions' are military units of the Roman army; 'Roman Senate' is the political governing body. They are distinct types of organizations with different roles and attributes and do not refer to the same entity.

Entity 1 refers to the power or authority held by the Senate (an abstract concept: 'senatorial power'). Entity 2 is the Roman Senate as an organization/institution. They are related but not strictly identical: one is an institution, the other is the power exercised by that institution. Therefore they should not be merged.

The two entities refer to different aspects of Roman state: one is the political authority held by the Senate ('senatorial power'), the other is the Roman armed forces ('Roman army' / 'Roman military power'). They are related (the Senate exercised political power and could influence military matters), but they are distinct organizations/collective concepts—one political, one military—so they should not be merged.

The two mentions refer to related but distinct concepts. "senatorial power" denotes the authority or power held by the Roman Senate (an institutional/political power), whereas "Roman ruling élite" denotes the social/political group of elites who ruled Rome and whose cohesion and competence derived in part from constitutional arrangements including senatorial authority. One is an abstract institutional power; the other is a collective social group that exercised or benefitted from such power. They are not strictly the same entity and should not be merged.

These are related but not identical. 'Senatorial power' refers to the authority/exercise of power by the Roman Senate as a body (a concept/collective power), while 'quaestors' are a distinct office — a group of elected officials who became members of the Senate. The quaestors contribute to the membership and functioning of senatorial power but are not the same entity as the abstract power of the Senate or the Senate as an institution.

These refer to different concepts: one is the authority held by the Roman Senate (a form of political power/office), the other is the territorial administrative units of Rome (provinces). They are related (senatorial power could affect provinces) but are not the same entity type or identical entity.

These refer to different concepts: 'senatorial power' is the authority held by the Senate as an institution, while 'magistrates' are the elected/appointed officials who exercised executive and judicial powers. Although related (magistrates' powers could be checked or restricted by the Senate or by the plebs), they are distinct entities (one is a collective institutional power/authority, the other a collective of office-holders).

These refer to different concepts: 'senatorial power' denotes the authority or influence of the Roman Senate as a collective political force, while 'Tribunes of the People' (tribunes) are a specific magistracy/office with defined powers and composition. They are related (tribunes could act as a counterbalance to senatorial power) but are not the same entity.

These refer to different concepts: one is the power/authority exercised by the Roman Senate (an institutional/political power), the other is the Roman citizen body/people. They are related (Senate's power pertains to Romans) but not identical entities.

These are different concepts: one is an abstract political power or institution (the authority held by the Senate), the other is the Roman citizen body/people. They are related (senatorial power acted upon or represented segments of Roman society), but they are not the same entity.

These refer to different concepts: 'senatorial power' is the political authority held by the Roman Senate, a political/institutional power center; 'Roman army' (Roman military power) is the armed forces. They are related (Senate exercised political control over the army at times, and army was an instrument of Roman power) but are distinct organizations/concepts (political authority vs military institution). Therefore they should not be merged.

These refer to different things: one is the abstract power held by the Senate (an institutional attribute or aspect), the other is the Roman Republic as the state. They are related (senatorial power is a feature of Roman Republic government) but not identical entities, so they should not be merged.

These refer to different institutions/functions in Roman government. 'Senatorial power' denotes authority held by the Senate, a body of elite magistrates; the 'plebeian assembly' (concilium plebis / plebeian council) is a distinct popular assembly whose decisions (after 287 BC) had binding legal force. They are related (both parts of Roman constitutional structure) but are not the same organization or entity.

'senatorial power' refers to the power held by the Senate (an aspect or attribute of Roman political structure). 'Roman Republic' is the state/political entity in which senatorial power operated. They are related but not identical: one is a specific power/institutional authority, the other is the state. Therefore they should not be merged.

The two entities refer to different concepts: 'senatorial power' is the authority or influence exercised by the Roman Senate (an institutional/political power), whereas 'praetors' are a specific elected magistracy/office within the Roman political system. They are related (praetors operated within the senatorial/magisterial framework and were often members of the senatorial order), but they are not the same entity and should not be merged.

The two mentions are related but not strictly identical. "Barbarian invaders" is a generic descriptor for various non-Roman peoples threatening Roman rule in Gaul; it is not a specific ethnonym. "Gauls" are a particular group of Celtic peoples from that region who made incursions into Roman territory. Because one is a generic label and the other a specific people, they should not be merged.

These are two distinct years (temporal entities). They refer to different calendar years and distinct historical events (Social War vs Third Punic War / special court). They are not the same entity and should not be merged.

These are two distinct years (90 BC and 509 BC). They are different temporal entities referring to different dates and events (Social War vs expulsion of Rome's last king), so they should not be merged.

The two mentions refer to different groups. 'Barbarian invaders' in the north threatening Roman rule in Gaul refers generically to northern non-Roman peoples (e.g., Germanic tribes). 'Carthaginian' refers to people from Carthage, an entirely different population and polity in North Africa/Mediterranean. These are distinct historical groups and not the same entity.

These refer to different historical events. The first is a civil war between Marius and Sulla (a Roman internal conflict in the late 2nd/early 1st century BCE). The second is the Second Punic War, a separate major interstate war between Rome and Carthage (218–201 BCE). They are distinct events, not alternate names for the same event.

The two entities refer to different classes: one is a group of Roman businessmen (victims in 112 BC) while the other is the institutional office/collective 'Kings of Rome' (early monarchs). They are neither identical nor alternate names of the same entity.

The two mentions refer to related but distinct concepts. "Mediterranean" (sea) is the body of water, while "western Mediterranean" is a regional part of that sea/region; they are not strictly identical. One is the sea generally (where Pompey eliminated piracy); the other is a specific subregion contested by Rome and Carthage. Therefore they should not be merged.
The Mediterranean and the Black Sea are distinct seas/places. They are related geographically and historically (both in Roman history) but are not the same entity.

One entity is the physical sea (Mediterranean) while the other is a regional/political concept — the Roman-controlled Mediterranean (the ‘Roman Mediterranean’) created by Rome's institutions. They are related but not identical: one is a geographic body of water, the other is a historical/political region shaped by Roman power. Therefore they should not be merged.

The River Rubicon and the River Tiber are distinct rivers in Italy with different historical roles and locations (Rubicon was Caesar's boundary he crossed in 49 BC; the Tiber runs through Rome and had Etruscan settlements on its south bank). They are related geographically but are not the same entity.

Both entries refer to the same geographical feature — the River Rubicon — described as the river Caesar crossed (noting slightly different dates). The names are variant phrasings of the same river and descriptions are consistent (boundary of Caesar's province; crossed by Caesar).

The Adriatic and the Mediterranean are distinct bodies of water: the Adriatic is the northern arm/part of the Mediterranean Sea, not identical to the whole Mediterranean. The descriptions refer to different geographic scopes and are not the same entity.

Pompey’s sons refers to multiple individuals (collective people) who are the offspring of Pompey the person. Entity 2 is the individual Pompey (the general). They are related but not the same single historical entity, so they should not be merged.

Adriatic and Black Sea are two distinct seas in different locations (Adriatic between Italy and the Balkans; Black Sea bordering Pontus). Descriptions refer to different historical contexts and geography, so they are not the same entity.

The Parthians were an eastern Iranian people/empire (Parthian Empire) and not the generic 'barbarian invaders' threatening Roman rule in northern Gaul. The latter refers to various Germanic or other northern tribal groups; it is a descriptive, generic phrase, not a specific name for the Parthians. These refer to different groups and contexts, so they should not be merged.

The Parthians and the Gauls are distinct peoples from different regions and historical contexts. Parthians were an eastern Iranian people (Parthian Empire) who were potential opponents of Roman campaigns in the east; Gauls were Celtic peoples of western/northern Europe who raided Roman territory in earlier centuries. They are not the same entity.

The Parthians and the Carthaginians (Carthaginian) are distinct historical peoples from different regions and periods: the Parthians were an Iranian people/empire in eastern Iran who clashed with Rome in the 1st century BC and later, while the Carthaginians were a North African (Punic) people centered on Carthage who fought the Romans in the Punic Wars. The descriptions given (Parthians as the eastern people Caesar planned to campaign against; Carthaginian as tenacious people overcome by the Roman army) clearly refer to different groups.

Both entries refer to the same geographic feature: the small river crossed by Julius Caesar that formed the boundary of his province and whose crossing in 49 BC precipitated civil war. The names differ only in capitalization and presence of an alias; descriptions are complementary and describe the same historical event and river.

Octavian (also called Caesar Augustus) is the same individual as Augustus, who is the adopted heir and successor of Julius Caesar. Julius Caesar is a distinct person (the great-uncle and adoptive father figure to Octavian) with different life events and roles. They are related but not identical.

The Praetorian Guard is a specific elite unit permanently stationed in Rome as the emperor's bodyguard and imperial police, whereas the Roman army (Roman military power) refers broadly to all Roman armed forces (legions, auxiliaries, conscription system). The Praetorian Guard is a subordinate, distinct part of the broader Roman army, not identical to it.

The Praetorian Guard is the imperial bodyguard and a specific permanent military unit stationed in Rome under Octavian/Augustus, whereas the Roman army refers to the entire armed forces of Rome (legions, auxilia, etc.). They are related (the Guard is part of Roman military forces) but are not identical organizations.

The Praetorian Guard were a specific elite unit permanently stationed in Rome as the emperor's/Octavian's bodyguard, distinct from the Roman legions, which were the main field army units of the Roman Republic/Empire. They are related (both are Roman military organizations) but are not the same entity.

The two entities refer to distinct groups: the Praetorian Guard was a specific, permanent elite military unit stationed in Rome under Octavian (an organized imperial body), whereas "Rome's allies" (satellites/allies) denotes the wide, heterogeneous collection of allied and subject peoples who provided manpower to Rome. They differ in scope, function, composition, and organizational identity, so they are not the same entity.

The Ptolemies were the Macedonian Greek dynasty that ruled Egypt after Alexander; Carthage was an independent Phoenician city-state in North Africa. They are distinct political entities with different geography, origins, and histories, so they should not be merged.

The Ptolemies were the Hellenistic dynasty ruling Egypt established after Alexander the Great; Pergamon was an independent Hellenistic kingdom in Anatolia that was bequeathed to Rome in 133 BC. They are distinct political entities and dynasties/kingdoms, not alternate names for the same entity.

'Ptolemies' refers to the Macedonian Greek dynasty that ruled Egypt (the Ptolemaic Kingdom). 'Roman provinces' refers to the administrative territorial units of Rome/Empire. These are different kinds of entities (a ruling dynasty/kingdom vs an administrative territorial system), not the same historical entity. They are related historically (some Ptolemaic territories became Roman provinces) but not identical.

The Ptolemies (the Hellenistic dynasty ruling Egypt) and Pontus (a distinct Hellenistic kingdom on the southern coast of the Black Sea, ruled by Mithridates VI) are different political entities. They are related historically as neighboring/contending Hellenistic states but are not the same entity.

'Ptolemies' refers to the Hellenistic dynasty/kingdom based in Egypt founded after Alexander, while 'Macedon' (Macedonia) is the separate Greek kingdom/region ruled by the Argead and later Antigonid dynasties. They are distinct political entities though both Hellenistic-era Greek states; not identical.

Actium is a city/place while the Adriatic is a sea. They are different types of geographical entities and refer to distinct locations (the Battle/port of Actium is on the coast of the Ionian/Adriatic region, but that makes them related, not identical). Therefore they should not be merged.

Actium and Capua are distinct ancient places: Actium is a promontory/sea battle site in western Greece (famous for the Battle of Actium), while Capua is a city in Italy that rebelled against Rome in the Second Punic War and was punished. They are not the same entity.

Actium and Athens are distinct historical cities/places: Actium is a promontory/site of the naval Battle of Actium in western Greece, while Athens is the major Greek city-state that appealed for help against Macedon and the Seleucids. They are different geographic and political entities and should not be merged.

Actium is a specific place (a promontory/sea battle site in western Greece) distinct from Rome, the city on the Tiber and political center of the Roman state. They are different geographical and historical entities and should not be merged.

The Ptolemies and the Seleucids are distinct Hellenistic dynasties/states that ruled different territories (Ptolemies in Egypt, Seleucids in the Near East). They are related contemporaneously and sometimes opposed to the same rivals, but they are not the same entity.

The Ptolemies (Ptolemaic kingdom/dynasty in Egypt) and the Hittite Empire are entirely distinct historical states separated by time, location, and cultural-political identity. They are not alternate names for the same entity nor directly the same organization/state, so they should not be merged.

Ptolemies (the Hellenistic dynasty ruling Egypt) and Carthage (a Phoenician city-state in North Africa) are distinct historical states/collective entities with different origins, territories, rulers, and histories. They are related in the broader Mediterranean context but are not the same entity.

Entity 1 describes 'Augustus's great-uncle who had been pontifex maximus.' That refers to a relative of Augustus (Octavian). Entity 2 is Octavian/Augustus himself. These are different people (a great-uncle versus Octavian). They are related but not identical, so they should not be merged.

Entity 1 is described only as 'Augustus's great-uncle who had been pontifex maximus.' That refers to a relative of Augustus (Octavian). Entity 2 is Tiberius Gracchus, a consul and elder brother of the Gracchi who was involved in persuading the plebs to unseat a tribune. These are clearly different historical persons from different families and roles: Augustus's great-uncle (likely from the Julius family, e.g., Gaius Julius Caesar's relatives) is not the same as Tiberius Gracchus (a member of the Gracchus brothers of the Sempronia gens). Their descriptions, roles, and family connections do not match, so they should not be merged.

Augustan benevolent despotism refers to the style and government reforms of Augustus' regime (regularized administration, army, moral revival) while Pax Romana denotes the broader period of relative peace maintained by Roman administration. They are closely related—Augustan rule helped create the Pax Romana—but they are not strictly identical: one names a governing style/administrative system specific to Augustus, the other names a longer-era condition of peace across the empire.

Tiberius was the adopted stepson and immediate successor of Augustus (Octavian). Octavian/Augustus and Tiberius are distinct historical persons: Octavian is Augustus, his predecessor; Tiberius is his adopted son and successor. They should not be merged.

These are different historical persons. 'Tiberius' as Augustus's adopted stepson and successor refers to the Roman emperor Tiberius (Tiberius Claudius Nero Augustus), while 'Tiberius Gracchus' is a different earlier Roman politician (a Gracchi brother, consul, tribune-era figure). Names are similar but refer to distinct individuals and time periods. No merge.

The two descriptions refer to different persons. 'Tiberius' was Augustus's adopted stepson and immediate successor (the Roman emperor Tiberius). 'great-uncle' described as Augustus's great-uncle and pontifex maximus refers to a different individual (likely Gaius Julius or another elder relative who held the pontifex maximus), not Tiberius. They are related by family but are distinct people.

The two entities refer to distinct things: one is a named event (Year of the Four Emperors, AD 69) and the other is a specific calendar year (90 BC) associated with the Social War. They are different in type, time, and content, so they should not be merged.

These are two distinct historical events occurring in different years with different causes and participants. The Year of the Four Emperors (AD 69) was a civil war over imperial succession; the Social War (90 BC) was a rebellion of Rome's Italian allies (socii) against Roman rule. They are not the same event.

The 'Illyrian army' refers to a specific army from Illyria that prevailed in a particular year (AD 192). The 'Roman army' is the broad, longstanding armed forces of Rome. These are distinct organizations: one is an Illyrian force, the other is Rome's military. They are related (both are armies, may have clashed) but not the same entity.

Trajan and Tiberius are different Roman emperors from different periods. Trajan was one of the 'Five Good Emperors' (first of the adopted emperors in the Nerva-Antonine dynasty) in the early 2nd century CE; Tiberius was the immediate successor and stepson of Augustus in the early 1st century CE. They are distinct historical persons, not the same entity.

'Illyrian army' denotes a specific army (Illyrian) that prevailed in the year after AD 192 — a distinct, regional/ethnic force. 'legions' denotes Roman legions, the standard military units of the Roman army across centuries and associated with the Roman Republic. These are different organizations: an Illyrian army is not identical to Roman legions. They are related as military forces but not the same entity, so they should not be merged.

Hadrian and Octavian (Augustus) are different Roman emperors from different periods. Octavian (Augustus) was the first emperor following the Republic's end in 27 BC; Hadrian was a later emperor (one of the 'five good emperors') and not the same person. No aliases or attributes indicate they are the same individual.

Nerva and Nero are distinct historical persons: Nerva succeeded Domitian as emperor in AD 96 and was an elderly senator; Nero was a Julio-Claudian emperor who died in AD 68. Their names, dates, roles, and historical contexts differ, so they should not be merged.

Trajan and Octavian (Augustus) are different Roman emperors from different periods. Trajan was a 2nd-century AD emperor (one of the 'Five Good Emperors' / adopted emperors) while Octavian (Augustus) was the founder of the Roman Principate in the late 1st century BC. They are distinct historical persons with different roles and attributes, so they should not be merged.

The Illyrian army is a distinct, regional force associated with Illyria and a specific event (prevailed the year after AD 192). The Roman army refers to the broader armed forces of Rome across periods. They are related (both military) but not the same organization or entity.

Hadrian and Tiberius are two different Roman emperors from different periods. Hadrian was one of the 'Five Good Emperors' (second of the four adopted emperors in some counts) in the 2nd century AD; Tiberius was the immediate successor of Augustus in the early 1st century AD. They are distinct historical persons and should not be merged.

Both refer to Roman legions as an organizational concept. Entity 1 names a specific group "Eight legions" stationed on the Rhine frontier, which could be a particular deployment or contingent, while Entity 2 describes legions in general across the Roman Republic. The first is a specific subset/deployment of the general unit type, not strictly identical to the general concept. They are related (one is an instance/group of the other) but not the same single entity.

Entity 1 refers to a specific incident: three Roman legions destroyed by Teutonic tribes in AD 9 (the Varian disaster in the Teutoburg Forest). Entity 2 is a general description of Roman legions as military units across centuries under the Republic. These are not strictly identical: one is a particular contingent/event (three legions lost) while the other is the general institution. They are related but distinct and should not be merged.

The 'Eight legions' refers to specific Roman legions stationed on the Rhine frontier, while 'Roman army' denotes the entire armed forces of Rome (the institution that includes legions). They are related (the former are components of the latter) but not identical: one is a particular grouping of legions, the other is the overarching military organization.

Channel (a sea frontier) and Gaul (a region) are different geographic entities: one is a body of water (the Channel) used as a frontier, the other is the land region of Gaul. They are related but not identical, so they should not be merged.

Entity 1 ('Eight legions') refers to a specific grouping of Roman legions stationed on the Rhine frontier, while Entity 2 ('Roman army') denotes the entire Roman armed forces as an institution. These are related (the eight legions are a part/instantiation of the Roman army) but not strictly identical; one is a particular subset/deployment of the broader organization.

The two entities refer to different kinds of groups. "Eight legions" denotes specific Roman military units (legions) stationed on the Rhine frontier — an organized Roman military formation. "Rome's allies" or "satellites, allies" denotes allied or subject peoples who provided manpower and levies to Rome — distinct communities rather than Roman legions. They are related (allies supplied troops) but are not the same entity and should not be merged.

Germany (a region in central/northern Europe) and Europe (the continent) are distinct geographical entities: one is a subregion of the other. Descriptions indicate related but not identical referents (Germany pressed by Caesar/Augustus vs. Europe embraced/cradled by Rome). They should not be merged.

Britain and Gaul are distinct geographic regions: Gaul corresponds to roughly modern France/Belgium and was the region Caesar conquered; Britain is the island (or region across the Channel) where Caesar undertook reconnaissances. They are related in the context of Caesar's campaigns but are not the same entity.

These two refer to different kinds of groups. "Eight legions" denotes specific Roman military units stationed on the Rhine frontier (an organizational military formation). "Rome's allies" or "satellites, allies" denotes subject/ally peoples who provided manpower — distinct groups of non-Roman communities. They are related (allies supplied troops to the Roman army and could be levied alongside legions) but are not the same entity.

Germany and Africa are distinct geographic regions; descriptions refer to different places (Germany in central Europe, Africa in North Africa where Romans campaigned). They are not the same entity and should not be merged.

'Germany' (as given) refers broadly to a region pressed into by Caesar and Augustus, while 'Gaul' is the region Julius Caesar conquered (northern France/Belgium) with the Rhine and Channel as frontiers. These are distinct historical regions: Gaul corresponds to much of modern France/Belgium, while 'Germany' refers to territories east of the Rhine. Although related geographically and in Roman military context, they are not the same entity.

Transalpine Gaul (southern France), a Roman province established 121 BC, is a distinct geographical and political region from Germany. "Germany" here refers to the region into which Caesar and Augustus pressed (roughly areas east of the Rhine inhabited by Germanic tribes). They are related (neighboring regions, sites of Roman campaigns) but not the same entity, so they should not be merged.

The two entities are different kinds of places: one is a body of water (the Channel) described as a frontier left by Caesar, the other is a land region/province (Transalpine Gaul / southern France) established as a Roman province in 121 BC. They are related geographically (the Channel borders Gaul) but are not the same entity.

These are distinct geographical regions: 'Germany' (a region across the Rhine pressed by Caesar/Augustus) is not the same as the 'Roman Mediterranean' (the Mediterranean region under Roman institutions). They are related historically but not identical.

The two entities refer to different kinds of things. "Eight legions" denotes a specific grouping of Roman military units (legions) stationed on the Rhine frontier — an organizational/military formation. "Roman provinces" denotes administrative territorial units of the Roman state/Empire — a regional/administrative concept. They are related (legions were stationed in provinces) but are not identical.
Rhine is a river; Gaul is a region. They are related (the Rhine formed part of Gaul's frontier) but are distinct types and distinct geographic entities, not the same entity.

Danube and Rubicon are two distinct rivers in different regions and historical contexts. The Danube formed a major northern frontier of the Roman Empire and was reached by Augustus; the Rubicon is a small river in Italy famously crossed by Julius Caesar in 49 BC. They are related by theme (rivers, Roman history) but are not the same entity.

Britain and Africa are distinct geographic regions with different historical events described (Caesar's reconnaissances in Britain vs Roman campaigns/Hannibal in Africa). They are not the same entity.

'Three legions' refers to a specific group of Roman legions destroyed in AD 9 (a particular event/subset), while 'Roman army' is the general institution encompassing all legions and military organization. They are related (the three legions were part of the Roman army) but not identical entities. Therefore they should not be merged.

'Eight legions' refers specifically to Roman legions (military units) stationed on the Rhine frontier. 'Roman Empire' is the state/political entity that encompassed those legions. They are related (legions belong to the Roman Empire) but are distinct: one is an organization/collection of military units, the other is the polity. Therefore they should not be merged.

The two mentions are different in specificity. "Teutonic tribes" refers to specific Germanic tribes led by Arminius who destroyed three Roman legions in AD 9 (a particular event and group). "barbarian invaders" is a generic descriptor for various northern groups threatening Roman rule in Gaul; it is a broad, non-specific label and could include many groups over time (including some Teutonic/Germanic tribes) but not strictly identical to the specific Teutonic tribes of AD 9. Because the instruction requires strict identity, they should not be merged.

The two referents are different: 'Romania' as a later name for Dacia (a specific territory/region in Eastern Europe) is a distinct geographic/political region, whereas the 'Roman Mediterranean' denotes the Mediterranean region under Roman institutions — a broad regional concept tied to Rome's maritime-dominated sphere. They are related historically but not the same entity or interchangeable names.

These are distinct geographical entities: Romania (a region / later name for Dacia) is a specific region/nation, while Europe is the entire continent. They are related (Romania is within Europe and shaped by Roman influence) but not identical.

These are distinct geographical regions and historical entities. 'Romania' (later name for Dacia) is a territory in Eastern Europe roughly corresponding to modern Romania, while 'Greece' is the Hellenic region in the southern Balkans whose culture influenced many later peoples. They are not the same entity and should not be merged.
These are two distinct geographic regions/countries with different historical identities and contexts (Dacia/Romania vs Egypt). They are not the same entity and should not be merged.

The two entities are different geographical regions: 'Romania' (later name for Dacia, in the eastern Balkans/Carpathian area) and 'Germany' (a region in central/northern Europe into which Caesar and Augustus campaigned). They are not the same place or historical entity and should not be merged.

The two entities are different geographic regions. 'Romania' (later name for Dacia) is in southeastern Europe, while 'Africa' refers to the continent/region in North Africa where Romans campaigned. They are not the same entity and should not be merged.

Dacia is a specific region (roughly corresponding to parts of modern Romania) conquered by Trajan. "Roman Mediterranean" refers to the broad cultural/geopolitical region dominated by Rome around the Mediterranean and is a distinct, much larger regional concept. They are related (Dacia lay at the edge of the Roman world) but are not the same place.

The two entities are distinct places: Romania (a region/country, later name for Dacia) and Cyprus (an island annexed by Rome in 58 BC). They refer to different geographic entities and are not the same historical entity.

Dacia is a specific region (ancient province/territory, later part of Romania) conquered by Trajan. Europe is the continent/region; it is a much larger geographic entity. They are related (Dacia is within Europe) but not identical.

Dacia and Africa are distinct geographic regions in antiquity. Dacia refers to the region north of the Danube (conquered by Trajan, later part of Romania). Africa refers to the Roman province/region in North Africa (site of Roman campaigns and Hannibal's defeat). They are not the same entity and should not be merged.

'Parthian army' denotes the military forces of Parthia (mounted archers, cataphracts). 'Parthians' denotes the people/ethnic polity of Parthia and in context are the opponents Caesar planned to campaign against. These are related (the army is the military component of the Parthian people/state) but are not strictly the same entity: one is a military organization/force, the other is the people/polity. They should not be merged.

The two entities refer to different peoples. "Chinese" denotes people from China; "Parthians" denotes the people of Parthia (an eastern Iranian polity). The descriptions indicate Chinese envied Parthian horses, and Parthians were the eastern people Caesar planned against — clearly distinct groups.

'Parthia' (a state/region) and 'Parthians' (the people of that region) are related but not identical: one denotes the political/geographic entity, the other denotes the people/ethnic group. The mention that Caesar planned a campaign against the Parthians refers to the people or polity but does not make the two names strictly the same entity. Therefore they should not be merged.

Parthia and Carthage are distinct historical states located in different regions and timeframes. Parthia refers to the Parthian state/empire in northeastern Iran, while Carthage was a Phoenician city-state in North Africa (Tunisia) and its inhabitants were Carthaginians. They are neither the same place nor alternative names for the same political entity.

Cataphracts are a type of heavy cavalry unit used by Parthians (and other peoples). Parthians are the people/ethnic/political group. They are related but not identical: one is a military unit, the other is the people who employed them. Therefore they should not be merged.

Parthia and the Ptolemies refer to different Hellenistic-era states/dynasties. Parthia is the Parthian (Arsacid) kingdom/empire in northeastern Iran; the Ptolemies are the Macedonian Greek dynasty ruling Ptolemaic Egypt. They are distinct polities with different ruling families, territories, and histories, so they should not be merged.

The Parthian army and the Roman army are distinct military organizations belonging to different states (Parthia vs Rome). They are related as contemporaneous adversaries and share the generic role of military force, but they are not the same entity and should not be merged.

Parthia is an ancient Iranian state/empire that was a distinct political entity. "Roman provinces" refers to the administrative territorial units of Rome/Empire. They are different kinds of entities (a specific state versus a category of Roman administrative regions) and are not identical or co-referential.

Crassus is an individual Roman politician/general; Parthians are a collective people of the east. They are different types and clearly distinct historical entities (one is a person, the other a people and adversary). They are related (Crassus invaded Parthia) but not the same entity.

The two entities refer to distinct military organizations from different states and cultures: one is the Parthian army (military forces of Parthia, noted for mounted archers and cataphracts) and the other is the Roman army (the armed forces of Rome organized into legions and supported by conscription). They are related as contemporary adversaries at times but are not the same entity.

Euphrates is a major river in Western Asia (Mesopotamia). The River Tiber (Tiber) is a river in Italy flowing through Rome. They are distinct rivers in different regions and historical contexts, so they should not be merged.

These are different groups: 'Parthians' refers to the Parthian people/kingdom of northeastern Iran, while 'Palestinian Jews' are a distinct population in Judea/Palestine. The text notes Parthians encouraged unrest among Palestinian Jews, indicating interaction but not identity. Therefore they should not be merged.
The Persian Gulf and the Adriatic are distinct seas in different locations (Persian Gulf in the Middle East, Adriatic between Italy and the Balkans). They are not the same historical entity.

Ctesiphon and Actium are two distinct historical places: Ctesiphon was the Parthian (and later Sasanian) capital located near modern Baghdad, while Actium is a coastal town in Greece known for the naval battle where Octavian defeated Antony and Cleopatra. They are not the same entity or alternative names for one another.
The Persian Gulf and the Mediterranean are two distinct bodies of water in different regions; they are related geographically (both seas) but are not the same entity.

The Persian Gulf and the Black Sea are two distinct bodies of water in different regions with different historical contexts (Trajan reached the Persian Gulf; the Black Sea bordered Pontus and was connected to Ovid's exile). They are not the same entity.

The two mentions refer to related but distinct concepts: one is the Rhine as a river, the other is the Rhine frontier — the river used as a frontier line. They are not strictly the same entity: one is a geographic feature (river) and the other is a political/military frontier/region defined by that river. Thus they should not be merged.

'Germanic peoples' is a broad collective term for many related tribes across northern Europe. 'Teutonic tribes' (Teutones/Teutonic) or 'Teutonic tribes' led by Arminius refers to a specific subgroup of Germanic tribes (often the Cherusci and other tribes) who fought Rome and destroyed three legions in AD 9. The second is a subset/specific instance within the broader category, not strictly the same entity. Therefore they should not be merged.

The Rhine frontier is a specific Roman frontier (region along the Rhine) while Europe is the continent/region affected by that frontier. They are related (one affected the other) but clearly distinct: one is a specific frontier/region, the other is the entire continent/region. Therefore they should not be merged.

The Germanic peoples and the Gauls are distinct ethnolinguistic groups in antiquity. Gauls were Celtic peoples in what is now France and parts of neighboring regions; Germanic peoples were a separate set of groups east/north of the Rhine. They are related as neighboring/contending groups but are not the same entity.

The two entities refer to different kinds of actors: 'Germanic peoples' are various tribal/ethnic groups living beyond or along the Rhine, while the 'Eight legions' are specific Roman military units stationed on the Rhine frontier. They are related (both associated with the Rhine frontier) but are not the same entity.

The Rhine frontier is a specific Roman frontier along the Rhine River, a boundary region that affected the history of Europe. "Germany" (here) refers broadly to the region into which Caesar and Augustus pressed — a much larger, distinct geographic region/territory. They are related (the Rhine frontier bordered/defined part of Roman interactions with Germanic lands) but are not the same entity.

The two entities are different types and clearly distinct: one is a collective of peoples (Germanic peoples) and the other is a geographic feature (the Rhine river). They are related in the description (the Rhine served as a frontier against the Germanic peoples) but are not the same historical entity and should not be merged.

'Palestinian Jews' is a geographically specific subgroup of the broader collective 'Jews'. They are related but not strictly identical: one denotes the entire Jewish people, the other denotes Jews located in Palestine (especially in a given historical context). This is a narrower subset, so they should not be merged as identical.

The first entity is the broad collective 'Italian' meaning the people of Italian descent/inhabitants of Italy. The second, 'Italian peasant', is a subset describing a social class (typical figure of the early republic, gradually impoverished). They are related (peasants are Italians) but not identical entities: one is a general national/ethnic group, the other a specific social subgroup/role. Therefore they should not be merged.

'Jews' (a distinct religious/ethnic people within the Roman Empire) and 'Romans' (the citizen body of Rome) are clearly different collective entities: different identity, culture, political status and role. They are related historically but not identical.

These are distinct collective groups: 'Jews' refers to a religious/ethnic people within the Roman Empire, while 'Romans' refers to the citizen body/political community of Rome. They are related historically but not the same entity, so they should not be merged.

These are distinct collective entities: 'Jews' refers to a religious/ethnic group within the Roman Empire, while 'Romans' refers to the citizen body/political community of Rome. They are related historically but not the same entity.

The two entities refer to different collectives: 'Italian' denotes people of Italian descent (modern/ethnic/national group tied to Italy), whereas 'Carthage' is an ancient Phoenician city-state whose inhabitants are called Carthaginians. They are distinct in identity, time, geography, and type (people vs state/people of Carthage). They are related historically (both Mediterranean) but not identical.

'Italian' denotes the modern/ broad people of Italy or people of Italian descent, a broad contemporary/national/ethnic grouping. 'Latins' refers specifically to an ancient Italic people centered in Latium (including early Rome and parts of Campania). They are related (Latins are a historical subgroup/ancestor of the Italian peoples), but they are not the same entity: different time periods and specificity. Therefore they should not be merged.

The two referents are different collective groups: 'Italians' denotes people of Italian descent broadly (a modern/ethnic/national group), while 'Romans' specifically denotes the citizen body of ancient Rome during the republican period with distinct political institutions and social characteristics. They are related historically (Romans lived in Italy and contributed to later Italian identity) but are not the same entity and should not be merged.

The two entities refer to distinct kinds of collective entities: 'Jews' is an ethnoreligious people/group, while 'Roman Empire' is a political state. They are related historically (Jews lived within the Roman Empire) but are not the same entity and should not be merged.

These are distinct collective peoples: 'Jews' refers to the Jewish people (a distinct religious/ethnic group) while 'Romans' refers to the citizens/political community of Rome. They are related historically but are not the same entity.

These are two distinct temporal entities: one is the first century AD (1–100 AD) and the other is the fifth century BC (500–401 BC). They refer to different, non-overlapping centuries and therefore are not the same historical entity.

Hellenistic civilization is the historical civilization/period characterized by the blending of Greek and Eastern elements after Alexander; Hellenization is the process by which Greek culture spread. They are closely related (one is the civilization/period, the other is the cultural process) but are not strictly identical: one denotes a civilization/period and the other denotes a process/phenomenon. Therefore they should not be merged.
These are two distinct centuries separated by approximately 1,000 years (tenth century BC vs first century AD). They are different time periods and thus not the same historical entity.

These are two distinct centuries (first century AD vs seventh century BC) representing different time periods separated by several hundred years and different eras (AD vs BC). They do not refer to the same historical entity.

These refer to different kinds of entities: one is a broad cultural/civilizational concept (Hellenistic civilization) and the other is a geographic/regional designation influenced by that culture (Hellenistic East). They are related (the Hellenistic East is part of or influenced by the Hellenistic civilization) but not identical.

The Hellenistic civilization refers specifically to the post-Alexander period (mixing of East and West) distinct in time and character from the broader, longer-running Greek civilization (ancient Greek culture, language, institutions, and spread). They are related (Hellenistic culture is an outgrowth/phase of Greek civilization) but not strictly identical.

These are different centuries: one is the first century AD (1st century CE) and the other is the third century BC (3rd century BCE). They refer to distinct, non-overlapping time periods, so they are not the same historical entity.

The two entities are related but not identical. 'Greeks of the Hellenistic era' refers broadly to Greek people across the Hellenistic period, while 'Greek cities (western)' denotes a subset: Greek city-states located in the western Mediterranean (including Spain) that interacted with Rome. The latter is a geographically specific collective (western Greek cities) and not equivalent to all Hellenistic Greeks, so they should not be merged.

The two entities refer to distinct collective peoples: one is Greeks of the Hellenistic era and the other is Romans (citizen body of Rome). They are different ethnic/political groups and not the same historical entity, so they should not be merged.

Entity 1 denotes the broad social group "Greeks of the Hellenistic era" — Greek people across the Hellenistic world. Entity 2 denotes a specific subset: Greek cities in the western Mediterranean (western Greek city-states, including in Spain) that interacted with Rome. The second is a geographically and functionally narrower collective (cities/communities) rather than the entire Hellenistic Greek population. They are related (western Greek cities are part of Hellenistic Greeks) but not strictly identical, so they should not be merged.

Hellenistic civilization refers specifically to the period and culture resulting from the conquests of Alexander the Great and the mixing of Greek (Hellenic) culture with Near Eastern elements; "Greek civilization" refers more broadly to the civilization and culture of the ancient Greeks across many periods (Archaic, Classical, Hellenistic, etc.). They are related but not identical: Hellenistic civilization is a subset/period of Greek civilization with distinctive East–West cultural mixing. Therefore they should not be merged.

The two entities are distinct collective peoples: one is Greeks of the Hellenistic era, the other is Romans (citizen body of Rome). They refer to different populations and political/cultural communities, not the same entity.

The first entity denotes a group of people (Hellenistic Greeks) while the second denotes a cultural process (Hellenization, the spread of Greek culture). They are related—Hellenistic Greeks participated in and were the agents/subjects of Hellenization—but they are distinct types: one is a people/collective entity and the other is a cultural phenomenon. This does not meet the criterion for being the same historical entity.

Both mentions refer to the same cultural concept: the civilization/cultural heritage of ancient Greece and its influence on others (including Rome). The names differ in phrasing but denote the same entity rather than related but distinct entities.

Both mentions refer to the same collective group: Greek people. The first is a general reference to Greeks; the second specifies the Greeks of the Hellenistic era (a subset in time) but does not denote a different kind of entity. This is a temporal refinement rather than a distinct entity, so they should be merged for a canonical 'Greeks' entry while preserving the Hellenistic-era alias/description.

'Roman thinkers' denotes a subset or social/intellectual category (thinkers, philosophers, political theorists) within the broader collective 'Romans' (the citizen body/society). They are related but not identical: one is a specific subgroup defined by role/occupation, the other is the entire people/citizen body. Therefore they should not be merged.

The two entities describe distinct cultural traditions: one is the civilization and heritage of ancient Greece (Greek culture/influence), the other is the culture of Rome shaped in part by Greek influence but distinct as Roman cultural identity. They are related but not identical and should not be merged.

Entity 1 ('Roman thinkers') denotes a subset defined by intellectuals/thinking individuals from Rome concerned with moral and political traditions. Entity 2 ('Romans') denotes the entire citizen body/political community of Rome during the republican period. These are different scopes and types: one is a professional/ideational subset (thinkers) and the other is the broad population/political entity. They are related but not identical, so they should not be merged.

The two entities describe distinct collective peoples: Greeks (people of Greece, including Hellenistic Greeks) versus Romans (citizens of Rome during the republic). They are related historically but are not the same entity and should not be merged.

Entity 1 refers specifically to 'Roman thinkers' — thinkers from Rome concerned with moral and political traditions (a subgroup defined by intellectual role). Entity 2 refers to the broader collective 'Romans' — the citizen body/political community of Rome. These are related (Roman thinkers are members of the Roman people) but not identical: one denotes a social/intellectual subgroup, the other the entire citizen population and political community. They should not be merged.

The two entities describe different collectives: one is specifically 'thinkers' (intellectuals/philosophers) from Rome concerned with moral and political traditions; the other is the 'ruling élite' — the political class whose cohesion and competence derived from the constitution. While related (some thinkers may belong to the ruling elite and they both pertain to Roman society), they are distinct groups with different roles and referents, so they should not be merged.

The two entities refer to different concepts: one is a type of art (Roman sculpture) and the other is the broader cultural sphere of Rome (Roman culture). Although related (Roman sculpture is part of Roman culture and influenced by Greek works), they are not identical and should not be merged.

Entity 1 refers to the people (the Greeks as an ethnic/collective group across periods, including Hellenistic Greeks). Entity 2 refers to Greek civilization — the cultural, intellectual, and material heritage produced by those people. These are related but distinct concepts (population vs. culture/civilization) and thus should not be merged.

One entity is a people (Greeks/Hellenistic Greeks) and the other is a geographical region (Greece). They are related but not identical: one denotes a population/cultural group, the other a place/region. Therefore they should not be merged.

Both mentions refer to the broad eastern Mediterranean/near-eastern regions influenced by Hellenistic culture and associated intellectual and religious movements. "East" as given (source of neo-Platonism and mystery religions) and "Hellenistic East" (region influenced by Hellenistic culture, source of Roman baths habit) describe the same general historical region—the Hellenistic/Oriental East as encountered by Rome. They are not distinct entities but different phrasings of the same region.

'Roman thinkers' denotes a subgroup of people (intellectuals/philosophers) from Rome, while 'Romans' refers broadly to the entire citizen body/political community. They are related (Roman thinkers are a subset of Romans) but not identical. Therefore they should not be merged.

Stoicism is a specific Greek philosophical school; Roman culture is the broader culture of Rome that was influenced by Stoicism. They are related but not the same entity — one is a philosophy, the other is an entire culture.

Entity 1 is the broad ethnocultural group 'Greeks' covering Greeks across periods (including Hellenistic Greeks). Entity 2 is a specific subset: Greek cities in the western Mediterranean (western Greek cities, including in Spain) — a regional subset of Greeks (city-states), not identical to the entire Greek people. They are related but not strictly the same entity, so they should not be merged.

Entity 1 refers to the civilization and cultural/intellectual heritage of ancient Greece (Greek civilization, cultural influence). Entity 2 refers to the geographic region 'Greece' whose culture reached others. These are related but distinct: one is a cultural/civilizational concept, the other a place/region. They are not strictly identical and should not be merged.

The two entities refer to distinct collective peoples: Greeks (people of Greece, including Hellenistic Greeks) and Romans (citizens of Rome/republican Roman people). They are related historically but not identical.

Epicureanism is a specific Greek philosophical school; Roman culture is the broader cultural milieu of Rome. They are related (Epicureanism influenced Roman thought) but are not the same entity—one is a philosophical movement, the other is a civilization/culture.

Entity 1 refers to the people (the Greeks, Hellenistic Greeks) while Entity 2 refers to the civilization/cultural inheritance of ancient Greece. These are closely related but are different entity types (collective people vs. cultural entity). They are not strictly identical and should not be merged.

The two entities refer to distinct collective peoples: Greeks (people of Greece, including Hellenistic Greeks) and Gauls (Celtic peoples from the north who raided Rome). They are different groups, time-overlapping but not identical.

The two entities refer to different kinds of collectives: one is a group of people (thinkers/intellectuals) and the other is a military organization (the Roman army). They are related culturally and historically but are not the same singular entity and should not be merged.

Entity 1 describes the cultural/civilizational aspect (Greek civilization, cultural heritage). Entity 2 denotes the people (Greeks), including Hellenistic Greeks. These are related but distinct concepts: a civilization/culture vs the people who constitute it. They should not be merged because type and referent differ (culture vs collective people).

Entity 1 denotes the broad, pan-Hellenic people of Greece (including Hellenistic Greeks). Entity 2 denotes a subset: Greek cities in the western Mediterranean (western Greek city-states). They are related (subset) but not strictly identical; one is the general ethnic/cultural group, the other is a specific regional subset (western Greek cities). Therefore they should not be merged.

Livy and Polybius are distinct ancient historians from different periods and backgrounds: Livy (Titus Livius) was a Roman historian who wrote a patriotic history of Rome; Polybius was a Greek historian taken to Rome as a hostage and known for a more analytical, Thucydidean approach. They are not the same individual.

The two mentions refer to closely related concepts but are not strictly identical. "Greek civilization" denotes the civilization and cultural/intellectual heritage of ancient Greece as a broad entity, while "Hellenization" denotes the process by which Greek culture spread and was adopted by other peoples. One is the cultural entity itself; the other is the diffusion/process of that culture. They are related (the latter describes the spread of the former) but not the same referent and thus should not be merged.

The two entities refer to distinct historical groups: one is the Greeks (a people/cultural group, including Hellenistic Greeks) and the other is Carthage (a Phoenician city-state and its inhabitants). They are different in type, identity, geography, and historical role, so they should not be merged.

Stoicism is a specific philosophical school originating in Hellenistic Greece and influential in Rome; Greek civilization is the broad culture and civilization. They are related but not identical—one (Stoicism) is a subset of the other (Greek cultural/intellectual heritage). Therefore they should not be merged.

'Roman thinkers' denotes a category of intellectuals from Rome (thinkers concerned with moral and political traditions). 'Latins' denotes an ethnic/linguistic people of Latium/Campania including the city of Rome — a broader ethnic group, not specifically intellectuals. They are related (Roman thinkers would be drawn from Romans/Latins) but they are not the same entity: one is a professional/intellectual subset, the other an ethnic/people group. Therefore they should not be merged.

The two entities refer to distinct concepts: one is an ethnic/cultural group (Greeks/Hellenistic Greeks), the other is a collective office/series of rulers of early Rome (Kings of Rome). They are related historically but not the same entity, so they should not be merged.

Epicureanism is a specific Hellenistic philosophical school; Greek civilization is the broad cultural and civilizational category that includes many philosophies (including Epicureanism) but is not identical to any single school. They are related but distinct entities.

'medieval Europe' refers to the region of Europe during the Middle Ages (a temporal subregion/period of Europe), while 'Europe' denotes the continent/region more generally and across periods. These are related but not strictly identical: one is the general place (Europe), the other is Europe in a specific historical period. They should not be merged.

These refer to different historical regions/timeframes. "Roman Mediterranean" denotes the Mediterranean world under Roman institutions and control; "medieval Europe" denotes the post-Roman, Middle Ages European region that inherited some Roman legal codification. They are related (the latter inherits from the former) but are not the same entity.

'medieval Europe' (a broad historical region/period in Europe after the fall of Rome) is not the same as 'western Mediterranean' (a geographic subregion around the western part of the Mediterranean Sea, relevant to conflicts like Rome vs Carthage). They are distinct places/regions with different geographic scope, time focus, and historical contexts, so they should not be merged.

'medieval Europe' (a broad historical region/period) and 'Germany' (a specific geographic/ political region) are distinct: medieval Europe refers to a temporal and cultural region across much of Europe, whereas Germany denotes a particular region/land that existed within Europe. They are related but not identical.

'medieval Europe' (a broad regional/historical designation covering much of the European continent in the Middle Ages) and 'Romania' (a specific geographic/political region and later nation, historically associated with Dacia) are distinct: one is a wide temporal-geographic region, the other a specific territory/region/nation. They are related historically but not identical.

These are different geographic/historical regions. "medieval Europe" refers to Europe in the Middle Ages (post-Roman Western/European polities and legal inheritance), while "Greece" is a distinct region with its own ancient culture that influenced later civilizations. They are related historically but are not the same entity.

The two entities refer to distinct geographic regions and historical contexts: 'medieval Europe' is a broad regional period/place in Europe, while 'Egypt' is a distinct region in North Africa with specific Roman-era events. They are not the same entity and should not be merged.

'jurisconsults' refers specifically to Roman legal experts (jurists) who produced legal commentary in 2nd–early 3rd century AD. 'Roman thinkers' is a broad label for thinkers from Rome concerned with moral and political traditions. The two are related (jurisconsults are a subset of Roman thinkers) but not strictly identical: one is a specific professional/legal subgroup, the other is a general category of intellectuals. They should not be merged.

Both entries describe the culture/civilization of Rome. 'Roman civilization' and 'Roman culture' are referring to the same broad cultural entity (the culture of Rome, its characteristics and influences). Differences are wording only (one emphasizes material monuments, the other Greek influences), not distinct entities.

Babylon and Rome are distinct historical cities with separate histories, geographies, and political identities. The descriptions reference Rome-specific institutions, events, and periods (Republic, Caesar, Senate) that do not apply to Babylon. There is no indication they refer to the same place or entity.

'Roman culture' (Roman civilization) is a broad cultural/political entity encompassing all aspects of Rome's civilization, while 'Roman sculpture' is a specific subdomain/art form within that culture. They are related but not identical: one is the whole culture/civilization, the other is a specific artistic component. Therefore they should not be merged.
The two entities describe distinct cultural civilizations: one is Roman culture/civilization, the other is Greek civilization. They are related (Greek influence on Rome) but not identical.

Atlas Mountains and Africa are distinct geographical entities: the Atlas Mountains are a mountain range in northwest Africa, while Africa (in these descriptions) refers to the entire region/continent where Roman campaigns and Hannibal's defeat occurred. They are related (the mountains lie within Africa) but not identical.

The Alps and the Atlas Mountains are distinct mountain ranges in different regions: the Alps are in Europe (crossed by Hannibal) while the Atlas Mountains are in North Africa. They are similar geographic feature types but not the same entity.

Entity 1 denotes the culture/civilization of ancient Rome (a cultural/historical phenomenon). Entity 2 denotes the people/citizen body of Rome (the Roman people as a political social group). These are closely related but distinct: one is the civilization/culture, the other is the collective people/society. They are not strictly identical and should remain separate.

Entity 1 refers broadly to the culture/civilization of ancient Rome (social customs, arts, architecture, Greek influence). Entity 2 is the specific field of engineering, described as a Roman innovation linked with architecture. These are related (engineering is an aspect of Roman culture) but not identical. They are different types/scope: one is an entire civilization/culture, the other is a technical discipline within that culture. Therefore they should not be merged.

The Atlas Mountains are a mountain range in northwest Africa (Morocco, Algeria, Tunisia). 'Southern Spain' is a region of the Iberian Peninsula in Europe. They are geographically distinct and not the same place — related across the Strait of Gibraltar but not identical.

The Atlas Mountains are a specific mountain range in northwest Africa, while the 'western Mediterranean' is a broader maritime region. They are related geographically (the Atlas border the southern Mediterranean coast) and both feature in Roman/Carthaginian context, but they are not the same place or interchangeable names for the same entity.
